column23:
This project aims to explore the effect of positive mood on an individual’s emotional intelligence, creative thinking, and Theory of Mind (ToM). Current literature suggests mood affects all three aspects in different ways, the study aims to add to the current literature by exploring these relationships further.
Method: At the beginning of the study, participants will be induced into two moods (positive and neutral) through the Autobiographical Recall method. In the positive treatment, participants will be asked to recall, as vividly as possible and write about amusing, positive, or enjoyable occurrences they went through and how they experienced them (in the neutral condition: participants will be asked to, recall, as vividly as possible, an everyday task, errand, or chore that they had completed). Participants are asked to think about this event for 3 min and have 7 minutes to write about the memory. Participants will be given 10 minutes for this task.

column23: The most amusing, positive and enjoyable event that occurred in my life was when I was surprised on my birthday by my family and friends. It was an event I would never forget in my life. I went to work on that day and worked very late. I was coming back home dat evening tired and hungry to the point I forgot that day was my birthday. When I got home and opened the door, my house was dark, I was very and I was surprised and almost furious. But to my surprise somebody turned on the light and the next I heard was happy birthday song. I was so surprised and I looked around my house and noticed the beautiful decoration and gifts. I was very happy. After they finish singing for me, they prayed for me. After the prayers, they offered me different gifts and there was a lot to eat and drink and we made merry. This the day I will never forget in my life

column32: I was cleaning the cooker hood of the hob (as we have just moved into a new home). I detached the extractor fan filters, the glass plate and some of the components and placed them in a basin of boiling hot water, dish soap and white vinegar. I let that soak for about an hour and then used a bristle brush to clean away the grease from each piece. This took several washings and about 15 - 20 minutes of effort. After this, I took bicarbonate of soda spray and sprayed that on each of the components and again took the bristle brush to clean through it. Once these were clean, I placed them aside and started on the cooker hood. I used the pink stuff to try to cut away at some of the grease - but first wet the hood slightly before placing that on. I left that for a few hours and then came back - again with a basin of hot water, dish soap and vinegar. I used both the bristle brush and a number of jay cloths to clean the outside of the hood, but I realised the inside of the hood was also filthy and I cleaned that out using several jay clothes. Once that was clean to a satisfactory level, I sprayed with bicarbonate of soda and scrubbed a little more and then finished off with an antibacterial wipe around the entire hood.

column32: The everyday task I am thinking about is giving thyronorm medication to my cat via an oral syringe. He has to have it twice a day, once in the morning and once in the evening. I tend to try and do it before his meal times to make it more of a routine. In each case, I will take the little plastic syringe and slot it into the specialised neck of the thyronorm bottle. The bottle is dark brown to protect the active ingredients from the sunlight. I then invert both bottle and syringe, and draw out a quantity of liquid. I cannot remember what this amount is off of the top of my head, but I have wrapped some red electrical insulating tape around the syringe which indicates the exact quantity needed. The use of electrical insulating tape always make me giggle, it has become a bit of a running joke in our family that we never have standard sellotape. At least in this case it is much more useful as it provides a good visual marker. Once I have this amount, I right the bottle and remove the syringe. My cat recognises the syringe and knows what's coming, but he is never afraid or nervous. Even before this became such a routine, it never really bothered him as he is so gentle and trusting. I let him sit down, and will either sit next to him or kneel, place my hand under his chin and gently put the syringe in his mouth. I will slowly push the plunger of the syringe and allow the liquid to enter his mouth, waiting between licks. I like to give him lots of love and praise, but I think that is pretty standard in our relationship! The whole injecting process takes less than 5 seconds, and afterwards I take the syringe to the sink and rinse it, ready to be reused next time. I then tick off that I've given him the medication on my tick sheet, as I can be quite forgetful and often worry that I've forgotten to medicate him or accidentally double dose him. Everything is ready for the next medication time.

column23:
A few years ago I went on a holiday with a really good friend. We went to Spain for a relaxing week in a beach resort. 
I had such a lovely time from the minute we got to the airport to the minute we got home. 
One of the nicest things about the trip was the amount of time we spent relaxing on the beach. 
Each day we would head to the beach to relax in the warm sun and swim in the sea. When it got to lunch time we would walk down to a little restaurant located on the beach. There we would eat pizza and drink sangria. I can still remember how lovely the food tasted. Then afterwards we would head back to our sun loungers feeling a little bit tiddly and tired but very very relaxed. We would then fall asleep listening to the sea. I loved the feel of burrowing into the sand, it was so so lovely. 
Then as the sun started to go down we would have another dip in the sea before heading back to get ready to go out to dinner. 
I think this was holiday was the nicest I have ever been on, and I’ve been on a lot, but probably the simplest one. I was very happy that week and felt I didn’t have a care in the world.

column23: One of my most enjoyable memories was a time recently when I surprised my parents with a trip of a lifetime to Walt Disney World. It was a secret I’d been keeping for a whole year and I wanted it to be magical. The planning process of course was so much fun, but the main part of the excitement for me was revealing the surprise. I’d enlisted the help of one of their favourites YouTubers and asked if she’d kindly make them a special video (disguised as one of her usual videos). I remember being poorly in bed, eagerly anticipating the video to land in my inbox. I watched with joy as she nailed the perfect reveal video and I cried with joy. As the day approached I was giddy. Giggling when no one was watching and smiling constantly. On the morning, we sat them down in front of the tv and secretly filmed their reaction. They were both in complete shock. I cried more joyful tears and soaked in their reactions. We hugged and screamed and spoke excitedly for the rest of the day about how I’d managed to keep it a secret, where we were staying and what adventures we had planned.

column32: Yesterday I cleaned the kitchen because I had a flat inspection from the estate agent today. I started by cleaning one side of the workspaces, so I moved everything away from there, cleaned it all, then cleaned the surface itself. Once this was done, I replaced things back where they should be, and cleaned the other half of the kitchen in the same way. I threw out food which was no longer in date, and I also had to clean the oven and the inside of the microwave as well. The kitchen looks a lot less cluttered now, and the surfaces are extremely clean. I also cleaned the sink and the cupboard underneath it, as well as the gas hobs, and all of these are clean and shiny now. It took a few hours in total, and I was very hot because it was a sunny day, but it looks amazing and I think it was worth it. Now I need to do a bit of maintenance on it every day to keep it looking as good as it currently does, since a bit of mess gets made there every day as me and my partner cook food.

I was with my childhood school friend who I had grown up with and always been close with. Thai job was very last minute so wasn’t meant to be working. It was a beautiful hot sunny day and we were wandering around the event doing data capture on people visiting the event. We were having a laugh together and enjoying the event. We hid in some of the vehicles to get out of the sun. And some of the other stand holders gave us cheeky drinks so we could sit and chat and have a laugh all together. One person caught my eye and I was drawn to him. Me and my friend laugh and joked about how good looking he was. Someone he was working with came along and i passed him my number and said do you know him very well does he have a girlfriend… and the guy replied “ I should do he’s my son” I was very embarrassed but 15 years later we are married and have two kids together best and happiest memory if not a little embarrassing

column23: One specific memory I have is about a holiday I went on when I was about 14 years old. It was a caravan holiday with my family (mum, dad, brother) to the Cairngorms national park in Scotland in the summer between school years. The weather was lovely the entire time and the campsite was set in a coniferous forest near a loch. We went into the little local village on day one and I bought 4 books - one of them was Dracula. I spent the entire holiday on a camp chair outside reading my books and it was the most enjoyable holiday I have ever been on. Dracula has since become one of my favourite reads, and I have tied it specifically to that holiday experience.

column32: An every day task that I complete is a morning daily dog walk before starting to work from home. The dog walks the same route every morning, he likes to walk along the quieter back lanes alongside the fields away from the main busy roads. I often reflect on these walks when I start to feel fed up or tired at work and remember that I started my morning with getting some fresh air, listening to the birds and enjoying that quiet time of day whilst most people are still sleeping- enjoying the peace and quiet. I remember the feelings of motivation, positivity and happiness the walk provided me with and how it sets me up for the day. The walk brings me joy, spending time with my dog and ensuring that the day is well spent, utilising time and getting to spend some time outdoors is good for my mental health. I enjoy seeing the familiar faces of other dog walkers that are out at the same time as me, doing the same route most mornings and enjoy watching the interaction between our dogs watching them play and have fun. The walk is part of our morning routine and once we get back I do the same thing which include feeding and brushing my dog when we get back home before logging on to start work for the day. On the days where I need to work from the office I feel sluggish and tired for missing that morning walk and it makes me realise how beneficial it is and how needed it is.

column32: One of the first things I do in the morning when I go into the kitchen is put the kettle on and make a pot of tea for myself and my husband as well as preparing us a bowl of porridge which we usually have for our breakfast.  While the tea is brewing and the porridge is on the stove I empty the dishwasher and if necessary also put out the bins if they have food waste in from the previous evening's dinner. As I empty the dishwasher I take care to make sure the crockery and cutlery is dry before putting it away in its appropriate cupboard.  Before making the tea, I take care to warm the pot before adding two teabags and allow about 4 minutes for the tea to brew.  I stir the porridge from time to time and get out some nuts and seeds that we like to have with our porridge.  Sometimes we'll have a banana with it and I slice that into a bowl.  I enjoy this time of morning as first thing in the morning there are lots of interesting birds that visit our garden and I look out the window whilst I'm doing these tasks and watch the birds on the bird feeder or on the lawn.  Sometimes we have woodpeckers on our peanut feeder.  We often have blue tits, blackbirds, thrushes and crows visit the garden.  By the time the porridge and the tea are ready, my husband joins me in the kitchen and I pour out the tea and pour the porridge into bowls and we sit at the dining table in the kitchen and eat our breakfast together.

column32:
It was 9 pm at night and my 8 year old daughter with autism needs help with brushing her teeth. I told her it was time to brush her teeth before she went to sleep as she was looking drowsy. She leaped off the couch in the living room to where I brought her to the kitchen counter where I brush her teeth. I lifted her up on the counter and put this special brand of toothpaste on her toothbrush. She is currently missing half of her teeth due to her age but many are starting to grow in which is causing some pain for her. 

As I'm brushing her teeth and trying to brush the more sensitive areas where teeth are growing in, she starts to grow visibly uncomfortable. I reassure her it will be over with quickly and that she has beautiful teeth growing in. 

Then, I give her a sip of water to spit out, help her off the counter and tell her to go to bed, which she does.

column23: It was my 19th birthday, January ,bitterly cold and thick snow.  I sat at home with my mum and dad, a bit sad as none of the Family could get there as the roads were horrendous.  We sat around the coal fire when we heard a noise outside.  My dad opened the back door and there stood my 16 yr old cousin, with his bike,having come 8 miles to see me on my birthday.  We pulled him inside but I couldn't stop laughing. His eyebrows had frozen stiff and he looked like the abdominal snowman.  There were white frozen snowflake stuck to him. He gave me a book, had a cup of tea then biked home. There were no mobiles to check he got home OK. But we had such a laugh and his love and determination to make my day special was unforgettable.

column32: So cleaning is on on my mind or rather has been on my mind. It is not just cleaning simply as we know it but it is cleaning a particular room. I usually help out my wife here and there to clean but then this cleaning chore has a rather sad story behind it. I have to help my wife clean up our late son's room. He was 2 and he died last year in September and ever since that day his room has remained untouched with no one sleeping there. Neither me nor my wife have felt strong enough to go through his things. The last time I tried to clean up the room I just found myself on the floor crying hysterically. We have to clean up the room and pack all his stuff away as we are now moving to a new place. Standing alone in his room makes me feel overwhelmed and defeated and a huge part of me wishes he would just run up and call me to play with his favourite wooden car. I hold his wooden car and tears escape from my eyes unnoticed and I find myself sobbing terribly. How can something like cleaning trigger me this much. I start packing up all his toys, followed by his shoes and I hold a pair of his size 8 little Jordans and it hits me hard that this little shoes will never be worn again and that breaks my heart to pieces. I did not know cleaning would trigger me like this but it has to be done so that we carry his things and memories always with us wherever life takes us.

column32: The everyday task I'm thinking of is going grocery shopping. The last time I did this I drove to a supermarket that's about a mile away from my house. I had a shopping list which I used to make sure I didn't forget to buy anything important, but also browsed for other items. I started with the fresh fruit and vegetables, then shopped the meat section, then the dairy section and fresh juices. If something I wanted was out of stock or poor quality or too expensive I switched it for something else, doing my best not to buy more than I needed. I put all the items into my trolley and paid for them at the staffed checkout. I paid on my credit card. Then I unloaded the trolley into some reusable shopping bags/crates which I keep in the boot of my car. Then I drove home and unloaded the shopping. I took the crates/bags into my house, put the fresh food into the fridge, the tinned and packaged food into the appropriate cupboards. I then put the bags/crates back into the boot of my car.

column32: We live in a rural village with only a small Co-op store.  It's a 25-mile round trip to our nearest big supermarket so we have grocery deliveries every week.  Sometimes we run out of something between deliveries, usually basics like milk or bread, so I used the Co-op for top up shops when we need them.  I'm disabled and have severely limited mobility, so I have to ride to the shop on my mobility scooter.  It takes about five minutes to get there, which can be quite a pleasant ride when the weather is good, though I avoid school run times as the main road to the shop is always very busy then.  I do this most weeks, and always look out for special offers and reduced short-dated food for the freezer, as we're on a low income and always looking to economise on groceries when we can.

column32: Everyday, in fact twice a day I make the journey from my home to my youngest son's primary school. If it is a sunny day and my eldest son has taken himself to secondary school we walk. The walk from our house takes about 20 minutes. We walk through a stinky path which has a sewage works on one side and an animal food factory on the other. We will then walk through an industrial estate and through beautiful woodland past a couple of friendly horses and up a ridiculously steep track called the bumpy track. My son and I will often play imagination games, pretending we are magicians, or best friends who have sleepovers and pizza parties together or dragons or many other things. When er reach the top of the hill we have to walk along a busy road which has a narrow pavement and lots of other kids and parents going along to school. There is a street sign that makes us laugh because it is inside a neatly strimmed box hedge with just a little post box bit strimmed out so you can read the street name. It just makes me laugh and I have stopped to take a photo of it before. column23:
I stood in my inexpensive white dress, outside Lichfield Registry Office, gripping my silk sunflowers with an overwhelming combination of excitement, love and good old-fashioned nerves! A far cry from my previous 2 weddings! Hardly any guests, just the most precious people to us and the memory of my beloved Pa, in his home city. 
To walk down the tiny aisle or, more accurately, the strip of red carpet, my beam went from ear to ear. The love of my life was watching me; totally awkward, hands in pocket, wild curls flopping over his face! A life-long disbeliever in marriage. He always said no ceremony or certificate could intensify his existing love for me so why bother? 
But he was the one who finally proposed to me. He knew how much I craved the happiness that I witnessed daily in my parents' 58 years of married joy. He wanted me to have that same feeling. 
And I did! And I still do. Every day. It poured with rain during our ceremony but we emerged to sunshine. It was torrential in the evening but only during our dance to 'Purple Rain'. So much laughter, love and true bliss that I've not experienced to that extent before or since. Perhaps love is all you need!

column23: It's hard to pinpoint a specific moment but for me  the most positive event in my life was when I decided to get divorced. I moved into a tiny rented accommodation with two small children. The freedom to have my own schedule and not worry about a second person and how he might behave when returning from a night out was a great relief as well as the time I could spend with my children as I also started doing freelance work so could be home for them.  Taking pleasure in the most mundane of things such as naming the resident wall spider Harry, and forging a comfortable home space  in which I revelled in the joys of reading as much as I could could and listen to music when I could in my free time,along with attending meditation and pilates classes is symbolic of the freedom to initiate the life you want for want of a better phrase. That ability to have my own space and taking pleasure in the simplest of things  was like rediscovering myself and gave me the confidence to  take the initiative with a lot of things in my life such as moving over to the UK and starting over.

column32: This morning I checked my raised vegetable bed in the garden.  I made the bed myself and enjoy planting vegetable seeds to use for myself and family.  I pulled out some older Pak Choi plants and cleaned that part of the bed, removing old leaves.  I then softened the soil ad flattened it lightly so that I could plant some spinach seeds.  Once flattened I poked holes, about one foot apart so I could place my seeds in the right position to enable the plants to grow and develop as best as possible.  Once the seeds were placed in the holes and covered with soil, I filled the watering can and carefully watered the bed.  I then picked some lettuce and rocket leaves from the plants that I had grown from seed two months ago.  In the patch next to those plants I decided to put in more seeds so that I would have lettuce in another month or so once the existing plants had died. column23: It is an amusing event.  I was living with my husband, we hadn't long been married.  We were very much in love.  But my husband teases me something rotten, and takes great pleasure in doing so.  And at this particular time, his thing was making me jump.  He'd 'boo' me often, and it wasn't a big thing, i'd jump a little and we'd laugh.  But one day i decided to get my own back.  I was upstairs, in my daughters bedroom (but i can't remember if she was born yet).  We must have been doing something like painting, because i remember i am in the room and by husband isn't.  But i know he is about to come into the room.  I hear him coming up the stairs.  So i hide behind the door - it wasn't really 'hiding', just stood behind it where he couldn't see me.  Anyway, i was dead chuffed as i don't usually think to tease him, but i was going to.  So i was really looking forward to it.  Anyway, as he steps into the room i jump out from behind the door.  I might have even said "boo".  I see what happened it slow motion.  He looked at me, and made this beautiful surpised face.  He squealed.  His shoulders shrugged upwards.  And then, he dropped the two pint glasses of water he was holding.  i didn't realise he would be holding drinks, and certainly did not think he would drop them.  Oh, he jumped out of his skin.  I couldn't breathe for laughing.  he laughed to - he was so surprised at this unusual behaviour from me.  He never jumped out at me again, and i regale this  tale to anyone who will listen.

column32: One everyday task I do is laundry! The first thing I do when doing a load of laundry is collect the dirty laundry. So when collecting laundry, I’m grabbing the hamper and grabbing dirty laundry from the floor, the bottom of the stairs, hanging on the back of my daughters bedroom door, etc. Once the dirty laundry is collected I make my way to the laundry room in the basement. I load (ie throw) the dirty laundry in the washing machine and add detergent. I don’t separate by colour or anything like that. It all goes in together. Then I turn on the washing machine and go do other things while that’s washing. When the load is done, I take the items out of the washing machine and hang them on drying racks. They take about a day to dry so the next day, I will load the clean and dry laundry back in the basket, take it back upstairs to the bedroom area, and start folding each item. Once all the items are folded they go back in the closet or in the dresser and the hamper goes back in the closet.

column23:
One of the happiest events in my life was when I was around 19 years old and my family took a vacation to Hawaii. I remember the feeling of excitement in the days leading up to the trip, imagining myself surfing in the clear turquoise waters and exploring the lush tropical landscape. When we arrived, I felt an immediate sense of peace and tranquility. One particular day, we took a guided hike through a dense rain forest area. The sounds of the chirping birds and rustling leaves made me feel like I was in a different world. As we walked deeper into the forest, we came across a waterfall that was simply breathtaking. The sight of it made my heart swell with happiness and I felt like I was in a dream. I remember the warmth of the sun on my skin and the cool mist of the waterfall on my face, while my siblings and I played in the pool of water at its base.
After we left, I felt an immense sense of gratitude for being able to experience such natural beauty and connect with my family in such an amazing setting. Looking back, that trip to Hawaii holds a special place in my heart, and I realize how lucky I was to have been able to take that vacation with my loved ones.

column23:
One of the most amusing and positive occurrences I have been thinking about recently happened when I was in 9th grade. I was selected to participate in an Olympiad along with two other learners who were also among the top three learners in our subject and within our grade 

As we traveled to the event, we engaged in a captivating conversation with our teacher. We explored various topics, with a particular focus on our future careers. It was delightful to share our aspirations and dreams, igniting a sense of excitement and curiosity within us.

During the Olympiad, our team worked exceptionally well together. We formed a strong bond and collaborated seamlessly. The atmosphere was a perfect blend of intense focus and camaraderie. We tackled the challenging problems with enthusiasm, leveraging our individual strengths and providing support to one another.

When the time arrived for the results to be announced, nervous anticipation filled the room. The suspense was palpable as each place was declared. Finally, to our immense joy and surprise, our names were proclaimed as the winners of the competition. It was an extraordinary moment of triumph and validation, rewarding our hard work and dedication.

The sheer elation and satisfaction we experienced were indescribable. We embraced each other, jumping with excitement and exchanging high-fives. The bond we forged during the journey and the victory we achieved together made the entire experience even more unforgettable.

This event holds a special place in my heart as it exemplified the power of teamwork, the joy of learning, and the exhilaration of success. The memory of that day continues to bring a wide smile to my face, serving as a constant reminder of the remarkable potential we possess when we work collaboratively towards a shared goal.

column23:
It is March 2021. I'm seated alone in the living room, the rest of my family has gone to sleep. The truth is I'm rather bored and I really shouldn't be. I'm attending the last day of the free five-day summit hosted by Lisa Nichols. I call her my 'Purpose mother'. Up until a few minutes later, she doesn't know who I am. Then, as fate would have it, she sees one of my comments on the live stream and immediately asks for me to be put on. I could not believe it! I raced to my bedroom, put on my bucket hat, and had an encounter that my spirit had long yearned for. She said my name. THE Lisa Nichols said my name in full. She has been my role model since I first heard her. She further gifted me the platinum tickets to her 3-day intensive summit. I have never forgotten that day ever since.

I'm running late. I'm sure he must be mad. I made him wait 2 hours for me and honestly, I would have left if I were him. But he's still here. "I'm wearing all black and a white bucket hat". He continues to describe where he is. I finally see him. Just perfect. This is the day my partner and I met for the first time. We had been in a long-distance relationship. We went to my favourite restaurant and a bird park afterwards. I had not been there since I moved to a different province 2 years ago. Everything was perfect.

column32: I stay at my parents house and they are away. Everyday I go up to the chickens henhouse. I last went this morning just before 8am, which is when the automatic door opens. I went to the shed first and got some seeds and filled up a tray for the chickens to eat during the day, and left some seeds outside the henhouse for the chickens to eat as they exit. There are only two brown chickens, the third has been missing. I watched one eat the seeds and the other drink from a metal container. I go back to the shed and get some different chicken food and fill the metal container that hangs in the small henhouse by opening the backdoor, pulling the container off the hook, pouring it in and placing it back and locking the door shut. I then lift the flap on the side and gather a single egg lying in the hay where the chickens like to deliver their eggs. I go back to the shed and return an empty container and close the door and return to the house and place the egg on a rack in the kitchen.

column32:
I had a serious accident about three months ago that resulted in severe damage to both of my knees, so the task that's been on my mind the most lately is relearning how to walk. I've been working through my leg strengthening exercises every day, following my physical therapist's orders, alongside trying to keep as fit as can generally while I can't walk.

Today, I stood up for the first time with the aid of a gutter frame. I sat at the edge of my bed, using my left hand to pull myself up, while using my right to help to support myself and push upwards, making sure that I'm distributing my weight properly between the frame and my feet before sitting back down and repeating. It's been a painful, slow process with a lot of difficulties, but I'm doing the best that I can.
